    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Body uniform orange in colour. Antenna 1 longer than 2, base of antenna 2 strongly setose. First two pairs of legs (gnathopods 1 and 2) with small elongate nippers. Last pair of legs enormously fat, with broad, flattened segments. Last pair of abdominal appendages with two short branches, the outer one ending two large upturned spines.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_199",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 6 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_200",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Restricted distribution from Gqeberha to Cape Town.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_201",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Appears to occur mainly on Hanging Wrack<i> (Brassicophycus brassicaeformis) </i>where it makes small woven nests between the branches of the fronds.&nbsp; Like in other amphithoids, there are spinning glands in the anterior walking legs which can spin silky threads used to construct the nests. The function of the highly unusual and greatly widened last pair of legs is unknown.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_202",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Probably feeds on the living tissue of the host alga <i>Brassicophycus brassicaeformis</i>.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_203",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like all amphipods the eggs are released in to a brood-pouch&nbsp; situated ventrally between the legs, where they are fertilized by the male and retained until they have developed into fully-formed young.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_204",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This is the only species in the genus, but it has been suggested that it should be incorporated into the genus <i>Sunamphitoe, </i>where it would still be distinguished by the uniquely enlarged last pair of legs.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_205",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Griffiths CL (1979). A redescription of the kelp curler Amphitoe humeralis (Crustacea, Amphipoda) from South Africa and its relationship to Macropisthopus. <i>Annals of the South African Museum</i> 79 (5), 131-138.<br><br>Griffiths, CL (1976). Guide to the benthic marine amphipods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>.",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_206",
